text:
Akshat, some opposite view point from my side. If you want to do something big and you have a plan B, there is very less likeliness that you will succeed in plan A.

I was doing a decent (maybe too good in some people's eyes) corporate job but wanted to be an actor since college time. To pursue that dream, I moved to Mumbai from Bangalore and also left my position as Team Lead in the company. My connections in company were good so they allowed me to do part time job from Senior position while I was working on my dream in Mumbai. I gave my 2 years to acting career, worked in 1 web series and then quitted. Reason? I didn't feel so motivated working in just 1 web series in 2 years! Also, I started feeling like I could make more money being an employee rather than struggling in Mumbai. And what happened next? I left my acting career, started doing a full time job. My job gives decent salary, close to 30L a year but I couldn't be an actor. My plan A didn't succeed. And I feel that this is just because I was having a decent plan B too, job. 

So I will repeat, if you want to do something big in your life  and you have a plan B, there is very less likeliness that you will succeed in plan A.

author: Sahil Jain

text:
Quite sensible. From most of your videos, it is pretty obvious that we must make educated decisions or take calculated risks. 

Ducks in a row - have our affairs in order and then have a plan of action with milestones along the way. Must include some fall back option or opportunity post-fulfillment plan.

As we are in the gig-economy now, everyone must plan for multiple sources of income/revenue. Never put all your eggs in one basket. New opportunities can be started on part-time basis and then grow it to supplement your primary income. In this day and age, lot of good opportunity can be planned and executed from your area (i.e. home or locality) itself as it must have an online business model for scaling purposes.
